---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const layerExample = `@layer legacy, settings, base, utilities,
layout, components, theme, hacks;`;

const whereExample = `:where(.flow > *) + * {}`;
const hasExample = `.field:has(.error-message) {}`;

const scopeExample = `@scope (.product-card) {
    .title {}
}`;

const containerExample = `@container (min-width: 36rem) {}`;
const stateExample = `.is_active {}`;
const modifierExample = `.product-card--featured {}`;
const utilityExample = `.vh
.a11y-link
.a11y-link--focusable`;
const themeExample = `@layer theme {
    .button {
        --button-background: var(--colour-accent);
    }
}`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="CSS Architecture Decision Trees"
    description="Decision trees for choosing modern CSS architecture patterns, utilities, theme rules, hacks, modifiers, state, and component structure."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Decision trees</p>

        <h1>
            CSS architecture decision trees
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Use these decision trees when you need to choose a CSS pattern,
            settle a code review debate, or avoid adding another layer of
            accidental complexity.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Decision tree sections">
        <a href="#start-here">Start here</a>
        <a href="#feature-choice">Modern CSS</a>
        <a href="#naming-flow">Naming</a>
        <a href="#utility-flow">Utilities</a>
        <a href="#theme-flow">Theme</a>
        <a href="#file-size-flow">File size</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="start-here" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Start here
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    Changing override behaviour?
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Start with cascade layers. Do not increase specificity until
                    you have checked layer order.
                </p>

                <CodeExample code={layerExample} />
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    Styling a component variant?
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Use a modifier class when the component has a deliberate,
                    reusable variant.
                </p>

                <CodeExample code={modifierExample} />
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    Styling temporary state?
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Use a state class for temporary or conditional UI state.
                    Keep it obvious.
                </p>

                <CodeExample code={stateExample} />
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="feature-choice" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Which modern CSS feature should I use?
        </h2>

        <div class="decision-tree">
            <article class="decision-card">
                <h3>
                    Need lower specificity?
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Use :where() when you need expressive selectors without
                    extra specificity weight. Also ask whether the selector can
                    be simpler.
                </p>

                <CodeExample code={whereExample} />
            </article>

            <article class="decision-card">
                <h3>
                    Need relational styling?
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Use :has() when the parent or wrapper should respond to its
                    contents. Use a state class when browser support or clarity
                    makes that safer.
                </p>

                <CodeExample code={hasExample} />
            </article>

            <article class="decision-card">
                <h3>
                    Need component boundaries?
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Use @scope when support allows. Otherwise use shallow
                    component selectors and keep child names scoped by context.
                </p>

                <CodeExample code={scopeExample} />
            </article>

            <article class="decision-card">
                <h3>
                    Need component responsiveness?
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Use container queries when a component should respond to its
                    own available space instead of the whole viewport.
                </p>

                <CodeExample code={containerExample} />
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="naming-flow" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Naming decision flow
        </h2>

        <ol class="decision-list">
            <li>Is it a standalone UI block? Give it a semantic component name.</li>
            <li>Is it a child of that component? Use a short child class scoped by the parent.</li>
            <li>Is it a reusable visual variation? Use a modifier class.</li>
            <li>Is it temporary interaction state? Use an <code>.is_*</code> state class.</li>
            <li>Does it describe the presence of something? Use a <code>.has_*</code> condition class.</li>
            <li>Is the name describing appearance only? Check whether a design token or theme layer is the better fit.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section id="utility-flow" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Utility decision flow
        </h2>

        <p>
            Utilities should be rare. Most styling belongs in semantic
            components, not presentational class chains.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={utilityExample} />

        <ol class="decision-list">
            <li>Does it solve a universal accessibility problem? A utility may be justified.</li>
            <li>Does it only describe spacing, colour, layout, radius, or typography? Prefer component CSS or tokens.</li>
            <li>Does the same group of utilities appear together often? Create a component.</li>
            <li>Would the HTML become harder to scan? Do not use a utility chain.</li>
            <li>Does it need local overrides? It is probably not a good utility.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section id="theme-flow" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Theme or component decision flow
        </h2>

        <p>
            Theme changes presentation. Components own structure and behaviour.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={themeExample} />

        <ol class="decision-list">
            <li>Is it a brand-level colour, spacing, radius, or visual treatment? Consider the theme layer.</li>
            <li>Is it component structure, layout, or behaviour? Keep it in the component.</li>
            <li>Is it a reusable visual value? Use a design token.</li>
            <li>Is it a temporary urgent fix? Put it in hacks, not theme.</li>
            <li>Is it a one-off hard-coded colour? Stop and review the token strategy.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Migration decision flow
        </h2>

        <ol class="decision-list">
            <li>Can you change the whole codebase safely? If not, add layers first.</li>
            <li>Is legacy CSS unpredictable? Move it to the legacy layer.</li>
            <li>Are components hard to find? Split them into partials.</li>
            <li>Are selectors too deep? Replace them with shallow component selectors when you touch that code.</li>
            <li>Can browser support handle @scope? Use scoped component partials for suitable components.</li>
            <li>Are overrides still difficult? Review layer order before increasing specificity.</li>
            <li>Is the fix ugly but necessary? Put it in hacks, comment it, and review it later.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section id="file-size-flow" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            File size decision flow
        </h2>

        <ol class="decision-list">
            <li>Can you skim the component file quickly? If not, review it.</li>
            <li>Is the file approaching 300 to 400 lines? Check for hidden sub-components.</li>
            <li>Are repeated groups of rules appearing? Extract or name the pattern.</li>
            <li>Are old hacks still inside normal component CSS? Move or remove them.</li>
            <li>Does the file own too many states, variants, or layouts? Split responsibilities.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Accessibility decision flow
        </h2>

        <ol class="decision-list">
            <li>Does this interaction rely on hover? Add focus and keyboard support.</li>
            <li>Does this animation move or flash? Respect reduced motion.</li>
            <li>Does this layout assume left and right? Use logical properties.</li>
            <li>Does this element receive focus? Provide visible focus styling.</li>
            <li>Does this component clip text? Test zoom, reflow, and wrapping.</li>
            <li>Does styling depend on JavaScript state? Ensure the HTML state is still understandable.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            When to leave it alone
        </h2>

        <p>
            Not every old selector needs immediate refactoring. Leave it alone
            when it is isolated, stable, rarely changed, and not blocking new
            work. Spend the effort where the code is active, brittle, or
            confusing.
        </p>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
